quote.p:
In that time, none of the Christians of Cordova was able to read Greek (
ighrīqī
), i.e. ancient Greek (
yūnānī
), and the book of Dioscorides was kept in the library of ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Nāṣir, in Greek, without being translated into Arabic. Thus, the book remained in al-Andalus while Iṣṭifan’s translation from Baghdad circulated among the people. In his answer to Romanos, al-Nāṣir asked him to send someone able to speak Greek and Latin to teach some slaves so that they would become translators, and the Emperor Romanos sent al-Nāṣir a monk called Niqūlā, who arrived in al-Andalus in 340/951–952.

                                    Ibn Wāfid took his residence in Toledo in the days of Ibn Dhī l-Nūn;


That is, al-Maʾmūn ibn Dhī l-Nūn.

                                    he was born in the month of Dhū l-Ḥijjah of the year 387 [December 997] and lived at least until 470/1077–1078.

div.p:
Ibn al-Dhahabī is the author of a treatise on the lack of nourishment in water (
Maqālah fī anna l-māʾ lā yaghdhū
).

Abū ʿAbd Allāh Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd Allāh ibn Ḥāmid al-Bijāʾī, known as Ibn al-Nabbāsh, took a keen interest in medicine and the treatment of the sick. He possessed a sound understanding of the natural sciences (
al-ʿilm al-ṭabīʿī
) and had good discernment; he was also acquainted with all other intellectual disciplines (
al-ʿulūm al-ḥikmiyyah
). He lived in the region of Murcia.

Ibn Khamīs al-Ṭulayṭulī read the books of Galen systematically and pursued the study of medicine, exploring all its methods. He was eager to learn the mathematical sciences (
al-ʿulūm al-riyāḍiyyah
) and devoted himself to that subject.

